## Part 1 ŌĆö What `fwrite` actually is

```c
size_t fwrite(const void *ptr, size_t size, size_t nmemb, FILE *stream);
```

`fwrite` doesn't write "size bytes" ŌĆö it writes `nmemb` *elements*, each `size` bytes wide. Internally it treats the memory block as size*count bytes and writes them sequentially as if calling fputc for each byte [Cplusplus](https://cplusplus.com/reference/cstdio/fwrite/) . The return value is **not** a byte count ŌĆö it's the number of complete elements successfully written [Cplusplus](https://cplusplus.com/reference/cstdio/fwrite/) . If that returned count is less than `nmemb`, a writing error prevented completion and the stream's error indicator (checked via ferror) gets set [Cplusplus](https://cplusplus.com/reference/cstdio/fwrite/) .

This is why the idiomatic check is `ferror()`, not just comparing the return value ŌĆö the return value tells you *that* something went wrong, `ferror()` tells you *whether it was actually an error* (vs. e.g. `size`/`nmemb` being zero).

## Part 2 ŌĆö What happens under the hood (glibc)

When you call `fwrite`, nothing touches the disk immediately. Here's the chain:

1. **`fwrite` ŌåÆ `_IO_fwrite`** ŌĆö glibc's internal entry point. It computes the total byte count (`size * nmemb`) and hands it to the stream's write logic.
2. **Copy into the `FILE`'s internal buffer.** Every `FILE*` has a `_IO_FILE` struct with buffer pointers (`_IO_write_ptr`, `_IO_write_base`, `_IO_write_end`). If the data fits in the remaining buffer space, `fwrite` is *literally just a `memcpy`* into that buffer. No syscall happens. Your 18 bytes against a default buffer of several KB never leave userspace at this point.
3. **Buffering mode decides *when* a syscall happens.** A stream opened on a regular file with `fopen` is fully buffered by default ŌĆö characters are transmitted to the file in blocks of arbitrary size [GNU](https://www.gnu.org/software/coreutils/manual/libc/Buffering-Concepts.html) (as opposed to line-buffered terminals or unbuffered stderr). The buffer actually gets flushed to the file when it fills up, when the stream is closed, or when the program exits normally [GNU](http://www.gnu.org/software/libc/manual/html_node/Flushing-Buffers) .
4. **`fclose` ŌåÆ `_IO_file_close_it` ŌåÆ `_IO_do_write` ŌåÆ `write(2)`.** Only at `fclose` (in your program) does glibc actually issue the `write` syscall, copying the buffer into the kernel's page cache. *This* is the point where a real I/O error (disk full, EROFS, quota, etc.) could occur.

So in your program: `fwrite` succeeded the instant the `memcpy` into the buffer completed. There was never a real chance for it to fail with 18 bytes into an empty buffer.

## Part 3 ŌĆö The actual bug

```c
int return_value = fwrite(buffer, sizeof(buffer[0]), countof(buffer) - 1, file);
// You write 18 elements (countof(buffer) - 1 = 19 - 1 = 18)

if (ferror(file) || (unsigned long)return_value < countof(buffer)) {
//                                                 ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ 19, not 18!
```

Walk through it with real numbers:

- `countof(buffer)` = 19 (array size, includes the `\0`)
- You correctly write `countof(buffer) - 1` = **18** elements
- `fwrite` succeeds completely ŌåÆ `return_value` = **18**
- `ferror(file)` ŌåÆ false (nothing actually failed)
- Second condition: `18 < 19` ŌåÆ **true**

You're comparing what you *actually asked fwrite to write* (18) against the *full array size including the null terminator* (19) ŌĆö two different numbers that were never supposed to be compared. The `-1` correction you applied to the `fwrite` call needed to be mirrored in the comparison too. It wasn't. So the `if` triggers even on a flawless write.

**Why the error message says "Success":** `errno` is only ever *set* by a failing call ŌĆö no library function is required to clear or set it on success. `fwrite` succeeded, so it never touched `errno`. It was last explicitly set to `0` by you, and `fopen` succeeding didn't change it either. So when `perror("fwrite failed.")` runs, it calls `strerror(errno)` on `errno == 0`, and POSIX defines that string as `"Success"`. The program is confidently reporting an error that the OS insists never happened ŌĆö because, mechanically, it didn't.

## The fix

```c
if (ferror(file) || (size_t)return_value < countof(buffer) - 1) {
```

Compare against the same `-1`-adjusted value you actually requested.

**One more smell, unrelated to this bug but worth fixing:** `fwrite` returns `size_t`, but you're storing it in `int`. It works here only because 18 is tiny. On a large write (`nmemb` > `INT_MAX`, or just on a platform/ABI where the implicit conversion truncates oddly) this becomes a real bug. Declare it `size_t return_value` and drop the cast entirely ŌĆö compare `size_t` to `size_t`.

